Pop a large #saucepan{} of water on to boil over high heat. We'll use it to cook the
rigatoni later. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).
Heat a splash of @oil{1%splash} in a #frying pan{} over medium-high heat.

When the oil is hot, add the @diced chicken breast{260%g} and @chorizo{60%g}(sliced). Season
with @salt{} and @pepper{}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat and its
packaging.

Brown the chicken and chorizo on all sides, turning frequently. This will take around
~{4-5%minutes}.

Once browned, stir in the garlic, @Cajun spice mix{1%tsp} (don't use it all if you're
not a fan of heat) and @tomato puree{30%g}. Cook for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @rigatoni pasta{180%g} to the boiling water along with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Cook
for ~{12%minutes}. Drain into a #colander{} when ready, then return to the pan off the
heat. Stir in a drizzle of @oil{} to stop it sticking together. Preheat your #grill{} to
its highest setting.

Stir the @finely chopped tomatoes{1}(chopped) into the pan with the chicken along with
@water{50%ml} and @chicken stock paste{10%g}. Bring to a boil. Lower the heat to a
simmer and cook until the chicken is cooked through and the sauce is thick and
tomatoey, ~{8-10%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in
the middle.

Once the sauce is cooked, pour the sauce into the pan with the rigatoni. Stir well and
season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Transfer the pasta and sauce to an
#ovenproof dish{} and sprinkle on the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}. Pop
under the grill.

Grill until the cheese is golden and bubbly, ~{2-3%minutes}, then get ready to serve.
Share between your #bowls{} and enjoy!

> If you've opted to get diced chicken breast instead of thigh, cook the diced chicken
> breast in the same way the recipe tells you to cook the diced chicken thigh. The
> chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.